Problem 1: Evaluating a Regression Model

a. Create a set of functions to generate data from the following distributions:

\[\begin{align*} X &\sim \mathcal{N}(0, 1) \\ Y &= -1 + .5X + .2X^2 + \epsilon \\ \epsilon &\sim \mathcal{N}(0,\, \sigma) \end{align*}\]

sim_x<-function(n) rnorm(n,0,1)
Ytrue<-function(X) -1+0.5*X+0.2*X**2
data<-function(sigma,n){
  tibble(x = sim_x(n),
         y = Ytrue(x) + rnorm(n,0,sigma))
}

b. Simulate \(n=100\) realizations from these distributions using \(\sigma=3\). Produce a scatterplot and draw the true regression line \(f(x) = E[Y \mid X=x]\).

  • Use set.seed(611) prior to generating the data.

set.seed(611)
n = 100
sigma = 3
dataset = data(sigma, n)

datavisual = ggplot(dataset,aes(x, y)) + geom_point() + stat_function(fun = Ytrue, color = "red")

d.Simulate a test data set of 10,000 observations from the same distributions. Use set.seed(612) prior to generating the test data.

  • Calculate the estimated mean squared error (MSE) for each model.
  • Are the results as expected?

set.seed(612)
n = 10000
test_data = data(sigma,n)


poly_eval <- function(deg, data_train, data_test){
  if(deg==0) m = lm(y~1, data=data_train)  # intercept only model
  else m = lm(y~poly(x, degree=deg), data=data_train)# polynomial
  yhat = predict(m, newdata=data_test)     # predictions at test X's
  mean( (data_test$y - yhat)^2 )# test MSE
}
poly_eval(0, dataset,test_data)
#> [1] 9.41
poly_eval(1, dataset,test_data)
#> [1] 9.294
poly_eval(2, dataset,test_data)
#> [1] 9.583
poly_eval(3, dataset,test_data)
#> [1] 9.648
  • Are the results as expected? No.We would expect quadratic model to give smallest MSE because we generate data from a quadratic model. However, the linear model gives the best MSE.

f.The MSE scores obtained in part d came from one realization of training data. Here will we explore how much variation there is in the MSE scores by replicating the simulation many times.

  • Re-run the same simulation in part d 100 times.
  • Create kernel density or histogram plots of the resulting MSE values for each model.
  • Use set.seed(613) prior to running the simulation and do not set the seed in any other places.

set.seed(613)
sigma = 3
ntrain = 100
ntest = 10000
n = 100
data_poly = tibble(deg=numeric(),MSE=numeric())

best_model = numeric(length = 3)

for (j in c(1:100)) {
  data_train = data(sigma,ntrain)
  data_test = data(sigma,ntest)
  res <- numeric(length = 3)
  for (variable in c(1,2,3)) {
    tempMSE = poly_eval(variable,data_train = data_train,data_test = data_test)
    res[variable]<- tempMSE
    data_poly = add_row(data_poly,deg = variable, MSE = tempMSE)
  }
  best_model[which.min(res)] = best_model[which.min(res)]+1
}

ggplot(data=data_poly, aes(x=MSE, group=deg)) +
    geom_density() +facet_grid(deg ~ .)

g. Show a count of how many times each model was the best. That is, out of the 100 simulations, count how many times each model had the lowest MSE.

tibble("linear" = best_model[1], "quadratic"  = best_model[2], "cubic" =  best_model[3])

j. Describe the effects \(\sigma\) and \(n\) has on selection of the best model? Why is the true model form (i.e., quadratic) not always the best model to use when prediction is the goal?

vary_sigma<-function(sigma,ntrain){
  set.seed(613)
  ntest = 10000
  n =100
  
  
  best_model = numeric(length = 3)
  
  for (j in c(1:n)) {
    data_train = data(sigma,ntrain)
    data_test = data(sigma,ntest)
    res <- numeric(length = 3)
    for (variable in c(1,2,3)) {
      tempMSE = poly_eval(variable,data_train = data_train,data_test = data_test)
      res[variable]<- tempMSE
      
    }
    best_model[which.min(res)] = best_model[which.min(res)]+1
  }
  best_model
}

label_set = c("linear","quadratic","cubit")
ntrain = 200


change_sigma = tibble(sigma = numeric(),count = numeric(),label = character())
for (sd in seq(0,10,by=0.5)) {
  best_model = vary_sigma(sd, ntrain)
  for (label in c(1:3)) {
    change_sigma = add_row(change_sigma,sigma = sd, count = best_model[label], label = label_set[label] )
  }
  
}

sd = 3
change_ntrain = tibble(n_train = numeric(),count = numeric(),label = character())
for (ntrain in seq(100,1000,by=100)) {
  best_model = vary_sigma(sd, ntrain)
  for (label in c(1:3)) {
    change_ntrain = add_row(change_ntrain,n_train = ntrain, count = best_model[label], label = label_set[label] )
  }
  
}


ggplot(data = change_sigma, aes(x = sigma, y = count, group = label, color = label)) + geom_line() + geom_point()+labs(title = paste("Counts vs sigma, with n_train=",200))

ggplot(data = change_ntrain, aes(x = n_train, y = count, group = label, color = label)) + geom_line() + geom_point()+labs(title = paste("Counts vs ntrain, with sigma=", sd))

As \(\sigma\) increases, the \(\epsilon\) term will dominate in data generation and the data will deviate from our original quadratic model. So later on, the linear model will have better MSE.

If we have sufficient data, the number of training set (\(n\)) will not influence the best model. The result is stable.

Sometimes the best model will be linear. Because of the variance in selecting testing data. There will be some fluctuation.
